metadata.name: Moonlit Sea #267
metadata.description:
A few years ago, my son and I went on a long-term trip to Taitung, Taiwan. One night on the roof of the B&B, we saw the moonlight falling on the pacific ocean. It was very beautiful and peaceful. We will never forget this scene.

Made with memory and p5js.

Variables:
- 24 palettes + random colors
- 5 moon shapes
- 2 island patterns
- 5 wave strength

Control(in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-res png image

metadata.name: September #74
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle ‚Äúlive mode‚Äù. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)

metadata.name: Expressive #3
metadata.description:
Expressive is my first generative piece ever. In this piece, I want to allow the randomness to take place. To me, making art is an activity of both freedom and complete control. And by freedom I mean the opposite of controlling the end results ‚Äì you just let it come, and let it be. I hope you enjoy the random outputs (but controlled by me, lol).

FEATURES:

‚Ü≥ Backgrounds
White, Black and Random Color

‚Ü≥ 12 Bases
‚Ü≥ 25 Tops
‚Ü≥ Up to 3 painting layers
‚Ü≥ Noises

Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save a PNG file.

metadata.name: ____ - Iteration 1 #59
metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ 0.1, ____ 0.2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

metadata.name: Leviathan #85
metadata.description:
Leviathan is a generative collection of large bodies made form particles, materialised from the viewers own subconscious. Atoms form gargantuan objects - subatomic monoliths and microscopic giants. Playing with the sense of scale it draws on the viewer‚Äôs subjective way of associating forms, a pattern that becomes a mirror, a skeleton for them to project. 

Part artist, part viewer. Leviathan asks us to question these relationships of creation, ownership and meaning. It is a chemical reaction that the artist starts and you finish. A colossal dream we are all sharing together - a leviathan.


Controls:
s or double tap: Download image
1 : Download 2400 x 4000
2 : Download 3600 x 6000
3 : Download 4800 x 8000
4 : Download 7200 x 12000

metadata.name: Cloverfield #36
metadata.description:
"Nature is the source of all true knowledge".

Have you ever taken the time to look, deeply look, at all the details in a humble patch of grass ?

In this tiny microcosm, a constant, fierce battle is going on, day after day, plants reaching out for sun, down for access to soil, fighting for survival. Smaller grasses form groups, alliances making it harder for taller ones to take over. Dead leaves remind us that some of them lost the fight, fallen warriors who, soon enough, will be forgotten too. Growth, decay, life, death, the endless cycle, right in front of our eyes.

It is fascinating, and, for me at least, an endless source of inspiration.

It is my hope that, through this project, you will take the time to take a closer look at nature, and that, as the pale blue dot we call home keeps getting drier and drier, remember that even humble patches of grass should not be taken for granted.


Key commands:
's' - save as png
'b' - make the background transparent (for printing)
'1', '2, '4' - set the pixel density, for resolutions up to 8000x8000

This updated version of the project should render on mobile devices, albeit with slightly reduced quality. 
If you want to save the image for printing, I recommend you do so on desktop.

metadata.name: Ethereal Microcosm #2
metadata.description:
An exploration of algorithmic organisms in a contained environment.

This piece is about the simulation of microscopic patterns using a high number of even tinier agents all following the same rules. Different species evolve and interact together, resulting in stabilizing patterns out of their parametric configurations. A form of artificial life.

This work is based on the paper "Characteristics of pattern formation and evolution in approximations of physarum transport networks", written by Jeff Jones and popularized in the artistic field by Sage Jenson. Some features were added to increase the visual and behavioral complexity of the system. Agents are divided into different species, with their own set of rules and interacting with their own substrate. Substrates also interact with each other and agents will mutate in contact of some of them.
